    {
      "orderIndex": 1,
      "slideType": "content",
      "title": "Community Health Centres (CHC)",
      "settings": { "background": "#FFFFFF", "block_style": "glass" },
      "blocks": [
        {
          "orderIndex": 0,
          "blockType": "rich_text",
          "title": "",
          "data": {
            "html": "<p>What is a CHC? • Not-for-profit • Community governed • Primary focus: improving health and well-being of equity deserving populations • Inclusive of those living on low income, new immigrants, complex mental health issues, and individuals without health insurance coverage</p><p>Services provided include: • Primary health care • Services that speak to the social determinants of health such as an education session to improve health literacy • Counselling • Screening clinics (e.g. – prostate/breast cancer screening) • Sexual health clinics</p><p>There are over 70 CHCs in Ontario. Use the link below to see a listing of them: <a href=\"https://www.ontario.ca/page/community-health-centres\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">https://www.ontario.ca/page/community-health-centres</a></p><p>Collaboration amongst PCPs, CHCs, and the Sickle Cell team is essential for improved access to integrated care that is evidence informed and free of bias.</p><p>Now let's take a look at 2 CHCs in Toronto, Black Creek CHC and Taibu CHC and the ways in which they provide services for individuals with SCD.</p>",
            "gridX": 0, "gridY": 0, "gridW": 12, "gridH": 3
          }
        },
